  "prompt": "How often do US inmates use smuggled cell phones in jail?",
  "response": "The use of smuggled cell phones in US prisons and jails is a notable issue, but precise frequency data is not uniformly collected or consistently reported across all facilities. Generally, anecdotal evidence and reports from various correctional institutions suggest that these occurrences are relatively common, with instances varying depending on the security level of the facility, the efficacy of contraband detection methods, and enforcement policies.\n\nIn some facilities, contraband cell phones are found frequently during searches and sweeps. These phones can be used by inmates for unauthorized communications, coordinating illegal activities, or accessing restricted information.\n\nEfforts to combat this problem include enhanced screening processes, more rigorous searches, the use of signal jammers, and increased penalties for possession of contraband phones. Despite these measures, the high demand for communication tools among inmates suggests that the smuggling of cell phones remains a persistent challenge.\n\nSpecific instances and data on the frequency of cell phone possession among inmates can sometimes be found in reports from individual state departments of corrections or through investigative journalism that covers the issue.",
